00:14:50.148 --> 00:14:54.068
and how this functions, in part at least, through activating the

251
00:14:54.088 --> 00:14:57.948
immune system. And then there was some work presented on how cancer vaccines

252
00:14:57.988 --> 00:15:01.588
may also enhance the efficacy of adoptive cell

253
00:15:01.608 --> 00:15:05.208
therapies, and that's shown in this example in a melanoma model

254
00:15:05.218 --> 00:15:09.117
here. There are lots of open questions, but I think that this is just

255
00:15:09.128 --> 00:15:12.708
going to be an area where we're going to see tremendous expansion and growth

256
00:15:13.528 --> 00:15:17.108
in the coming years. So I really look forward

257
00:15:17.508 --> 00:15:19.208
to seeing how this field develops.

258
00:15:20.768 --> 00:15:24.628
Well, with all of these therapies, with new therapies, with older

259
00:15:24.648 --> 00:15:28.628
therapies, we unfortunately have the problem of drug resistance and of

260
00:15:28.688 --> 00:15:31.868
minimal residual disease. And so

261
00:15:32.608 --> 00:15:36.308
we saw that this is an area of

262
00:15:36.388 --> 00:15:40.008
emphasis for many investigators in the field.

263
00:15:40.068 --> 00:15:44.008
We saw a session, opening plenary session, that really set

264
00:15:44.068 --> 00:15:47.808
the groundwork for where we

265
00:15:47.908 --> 00:15:51.728
are in our understanding of minimal residual disease and really pointed

266
00:15:51.808 --> 00:15:55.488
out how there are two types of minimal residual disease, the persister

267
00:15:55.588 --> 00:15:57.308
cells that are left over after

268
00:15:57.368 --> 00:16:01.188
systemic treatment, and that give

269
00:16:01.268 --> 00:16:05.248
rise to the resistant state, and then also the situation in

270
00:16:05.288 --> 00:16:09.188
which you have micrometastatic disease that is present after

271
00:16:09.228 --> 00:16:12.188
local therapy. So kind of two different settings.

272
00:16:12.648 --> 00:16:16.508
When thinking about the first setting, we saw presentations on

273
00:16:16.548 --> 00:16:20.308
the biology of this minimal residual disease, of these persister

274
00:16:20.348 --> 00:16:23.788
cells, and how the persister cells can co-opt

275
00:16:23.948 --> 00:16:27.928
different injury repair states and

276
00:16:27.988 --> 00:16:31.878
interact with cells in the microenvironment that help them survive and

277
00:16:32.568 --> 00:16:36.168
give rise to the resistant state. We also learned that

278
00:16:36.188 --> 00:16:39.428
plasticity of the minimal residual disease is

279
00:16:39.488 --> 00:16:43.348
really an important component of that state, and so that

280
00:16:43.368 --> 00:16:45.508
heterogeneity is really challenging.

281
00:16:46.108 --> 00:16:46.428
And

282
00:16:47.448 --> 00:16:51.428
in one of the presentations, there's sort of a forward-looking presentation by

283
00:16:51.448 --> 00:16:54.988
Chris Marine about how maybe we could take these cells and

284
00:16:55.068 --> 00:16:58.708
direct them to a certain state with a specific type of

285
00:16:58.768 --> 00:17:02.668
treatment. And then maybe we can use other approaches, and he proposed to

286
00:17:02.728 --> 00:17:06.449
use a morphometric approach based on cell surface area and volume

287
00:17:06.929 --> 00:17:10.288
to really select the cells and then target those cells.

288
00:17:10.628 --> 00:17:13.748
So some things to think about. In the context of

289
00:17:13.868 --> 00:17:17.388
micrometastatic disease present after local therapy, for

290
00:17:17.449 --> 00:17:20.768
example, I think we're really in early

291
00:17:20.908 --> 00:17:24.828
stages of learning about the potential of ctDNA and

292
00:17:24.868 --> 00:17:28.648
how ctDNA-informed decisions can actually be used to

293
00:17:28.688 --> 00:17:30.568
escalate and deescalate therapy.

294
00:17:30.608 --> 00:17:34.228
There are a lot of nuances here, different situations for

295
00:17:34.268 --> 00:17:37.968
different cancer types and for different therapies that are being used.

296
00:17:38.008 --> 00:17:40.328
So I think there's a lot of work to do there.

297
00:17:40.668 --> 00:17:43.948
We also saw that some of the approaches now

298
00:17:44.808 --> 00:17:48.608
that we can use for monitoring circulating tumor DNA are

299
00:17:48.648 --> 00:17:52.508
really advancing, and even the potential of using plasma whole

300
00:17:52.608 --> 00:17:56.448
genome sequencing for MRD monitoring that was talked

301
00:17:56.528 --> 00:17:59.548
about by Dan Landau in his plenary

302
00:17:59.568 --> 00:18:03.312
presentation. WellWhat about resistance?

303
00:18:03.492 --> 00:18:07.342
And one of the areas where there's a lot of work that

304
00:18:07.392 --> 00:18:11.382
is happening currently is really understanding this plasticity

305
00:18:11.412 --> 00:18:15.032
that happens as tumors become resistant to therapy.

306
00:18:15.612 --> 00:18:19.492
And this is very daunting because there isn't a specific

307
00:18:19.572 --> 00:18:22.952
mutation, for example, that the cells are dependent on, or things that we

308
00:18:22.992 --> 00:18:26.912
can think of targeting easily. But what we're beginning to learn is we're

309
00:18:26.952 --> 00:18:30.262
beginning to learn about the pathways and the processes

310
00:18:30.792 --> 00:18:32.242
that really can

311
00:18:33.052 --> 00:18:36.772
determine the phenotype of a specific

312
00:18:36.782 --> 00:18:40.352
tumor at resistance. And Charles Sawyers talked about the

313
00:18:40.372 --> 00:18:43.952
involvement of YAP/TEAD, Notch, and androgen receptor

314
00:18:44.092 --> 00:18:48.052
signaling in determining in prostate cancer whether tumors

315
00:18:48.092 --> 00:18:52.032
will have an adenocarcinoma phenotype or go down a

316
00:18:52.042 --> 00:18:55.622
neuroendocrine route. And with that knowledge,

317
00:18:56.172 --> 00:19:00.112
then we also can think of therapeutically targeting the

318
00:19:00.132 --> 00:19:04.052
specific lineages and identifying vulnerabilities of those lineages.

319
00:19:05.352 --> 00:19:08.512
Other data that is emerging is really on

320
00:19:09.892 --> 00:19:13.552
the biology of this plasticity. Why is it that there are some

321
00:19:13.892 --> 00:19:17.592
situations in which tumors can kind of take these different route?

322
00:19:17.852 --> 00:19:21.512
Why aren't they constrained in the way that one would expect them to be?

323
00:19:22.032 --> 00:19:25.772
And there was work from Dr. Posovich showing how SMARCA4

324
00:19:25.992 --> 00:19:29.532
deficiency really allows and enables a cell state

325
00:19:29.612 --> 00:19:32.982
disorder and promotes sort of random transitions between

326
00:19:33.072 --> 00:19:36.832
transcriptional states. And this, as you can imagine, can make it very

327
00:19:36.872 --> 00:19:40.842
difficult to figure out how to treat the tumor because

328
00:19:40.872 --> 00:19:43.622
it can take different routes and be very aggressive.

329
00:19:44.062 --> 00:19:47.572
And so all of this knowledge is really going to help us

330
00:19:47.932 --> 00:19:51.852
identify novel targets for specific lineage states in the future.

331
00:19:53.512 --> 00:19:53.652
So

332
00:19:54.712 --> 00:19:57.792
I'd like to move on to the fourth topic, which is the cancer

333
00:19:57.912 --> 00:20:01.852
genome. And when we think of the cancer genome, I think one of the

334
00:20:01.912 --> 00:20:05.792
things that really has come out of the meeting this year is that we have

335
00:20:05.832 --> 00:20:09.692
the opportunity with some of the ways in which we can probe

336
00:20:09.732 --> 00:20:13.512
the genome to really get better insight into chromosomal

337
00:20:13.532 --> 00:20:16.132
instability and structural variants.

338
00:20:16.202 --> 00:20:20.072
And in particular, this comes from the fact that now we have very

339
00:20:20.212 --> 00:20:22.792
rich whole-genome sequencing data sets.

340
00:20:23.312 --> 00:20:26.712
And just to point out, there's been an expansion of

341
00:20:26.772 --> 00:20:30.532
TCGA data, whole-genome sequencing data,

342
00:20:31.092 --> 00:20:34.612
deep sequencing of 8,500 tumor normal

343
00:20:34.712 --> 00:20:38.692
pairs that are now downloadable. And there's also been the development

344
00:20:38.712 --> 00:20:42.452
of bioinformatic tools to be able to study these

345
00:20:42.492 --> 00:20:46.392
data sets, whole-genome sequencing data, and really understand structural

346
00:20:46.492 --> 00:20:49.992
variants in these data. This is really important

347
00:20:50.172 --> 00:20:53.652
because with this information then, we can start to

348
00:20:53.712 --> 00:20:57.692
understand how these structural variants are related to different

349
00:20:57.752 --> 00:21:00.492
treatments and different treatment modalities.

350
00:21:00.522 --> 00:21:03.992
And it's going to help us in the future really understand tumor

351
00:21:04.032 --> 00:21:07.312
evolution and cancer drivers, again, both

352
00:21:07.352 --> 00:21:11.192
of which have implications for how we treat tumors.

353
00:21:12.332 --> 00:21:16.232
So last but not least, I'd like to tell you

354
00:21:16.292 --> 00:21:20.052
about some of the work on the tumor micro and the tumor macro

355
00:21:20.232 --> 00:21:22.941
environments that was covered at this meeting.

356
00:21:22.992 --> 00:21:26.902
For sure, I will not do this topic justice, but I'm going to talk about

357
00:21:26.902 --> 00:21:29.032
a couple of different things that emerged.

358
00:21:29.712 --> 00:21:30.292
First of all,

359
00:21:31.812 --> 00:21:35.552
we saw a lot of presentations and a lot of research

360
00:21:36.912 --> 00:21:40.712
to understand immune evasion. And this is really important

361
00:21:40.732 --> 00:21:44.402
because to be able to deploy immune checkpoint blockade and other

362
00:21:44.432 --> 00:21:48.212
cancer immunotherapies, we need to understand mechanisms

363
00:21:48.312 --> 00:21:49.672
of immune evasion.

364
00:21:50.512 --> 00:21:54.072
We see deep and rigorous work into

365
00:21:54.132 --> 00:21:57.592
understanding the biology of T cells through

366
00:21:57.652 --> 00:22:00.252
treatment with immune checkpoint inhibitors.

367
00:22:00.282 --> 00:22:03.712
And in a presentation from John Wherry, we saw an

368
00:22:03.792 --> 00:22:07.312
analysis, for example, of the T cells showing that maybe

369
00:22:07.352 --> 00:22:11.342
continuous treatment with PD-1 isn't the best because we don't have

370
00:22:11.372 --> 00:22:14.152
those most functional T cells there anymore.

371
00:22:14.162 --> 00:22:17.952
And so maybe we need to think of other approaches to treat with

372
00:22:18.032 --> 00:22:21.911
anti-PD-1 therapy to maximize the functionality of

373
00:22:21.952 --> 00:22:25.692
T cells. We saw also some work in pediatric

374
00:22:25.712 --> 00:22:29.652
brain tumors in a very interesting

375
00:22:30.552 --> 00:22:33.612
way in which the tumor can actually mediate

376
00:22:33.652 --> 00:22:37.532
immunosuppression through the CSF, the

377
00:22:37.592 --> 00:22:41.522
cerebrospinal fluid, essentially leading to

378
00:22:42.312 --> 00:22:46.272
an expansion of hematopoietic stem cell progenitor cells

379
00:22:46.312 --> 00:22:50.002
in the skull, and that then in the tumor microenvironment, these

380
00:22:50.032 --> 00:22:53.752
become immunosuppressive MDSCs and Tregs.

381
00:22:53.792 --> 00:22:57.012
And so you create that immunosuppressive microenvironment.

382
00:22:57.032 --> 00:23:00.592
But figuring out that pathway and that loop can help

383
00:23:00.652 --> 00:23:04.642
interrupt it so that then we can get other

384
00:23:04.652 --> 00:23:07.992
therapies to work better. And also we saw

385
00:23:08.112 --> 00:23:12.002
presentations in the context of hematological malignancies on how

386
00:23:12.432 --> 00:23:15.712
we can leverage epigenetic processes and epigenetic

387
00:23:15.872 --> 00:23:16.532
priming

388
00:23:17.612 --> 00:23:19.412
to really help

389
00:23:20.352 --> 00:23:24.312
work in conjunction then with different types of T cell immunotherapies.

390
00:23:24.352 --> 00:23:26.052
So that's kind of a direction in which

391
00:23:27.252 --> 00:23:28.562
some of that work is going.

392
00:23:29.832 --> 00:23:33.712
I'd also like to highlight how there are new technologies that allow

393
00:23:33.752 --> 00:23:37.482
us to study immune evasion. Cathy Wu showed an approach called

394
00:23:37.632 --> 00:23:40.172
Slide and Go Tag, in which you can

395
00:23:41.052 --> 00:23:44.392
examine the T cell state, TCR neoantigen

396
00:23:44.432 --> 00:23:47.952
localization, and much more in the tumor microenvironment

397
00:23:48.452 --> 00:23:52.352
on a single slide. And so that can be very powerful

398
00:23:52.392 --> 00:23:55.622
for us to really gain more insight into

399
00:23:56.112 --> 00:24:00.036
mechanisms of immune evasion.We know that

400
00:24:00.156 --> 00:24:04.136
cancer is a systemic disease, and we know there

401
00:24:04.156 --> 00:24:07.836
were presentations on cachexia, presentations on

402
00:24:08.556 --> 00:24:12.086
processes like metabolic disorders.

403
00:24:13.216 --> 00:24:16.326
One of the things that I'd like to point out that I think is really

404
00:24:16.576 --> 00:24:20.256
maturing right now in the field and really coming to the forefront is our

405
00:24:20.266 --> 00:24:24.056
understanding of the interaction between the

406
00:24:24.096 --> 00:24:28.056
nervous system and cancer. And in particular, the nervous system

407
00:24:28.066 --> 00:24:30.416
and how this affects the immune system and cancer.

408
00:24:31.856 --> 00:24:35.676
This is kind of challenging because what I learned is that when you're

409
00:24:35.696 --> 00:24:39.356
thinking of the nervous system, nerve endings are in tumors,

410
00:24:39.816 --> 00:24:43.696
but the nerve cell body is not. So you actually need to

411
00:24:43.736 --> 00:24:47.526
develop approaches in which you can trace the nerves and

412
00:24:47.576 --> 00:24:51.536
identify the nerves that innervate an organ or a tissue so that then

413
00:24:51.596 --> 00:24:55.496
you can study what are the molecular features of those nerves

414
00:24:55.556 --> 00:24:58.296
in a tumor situation versus a normal tissue.

415
00:24:58.346 --> 00:25:02.026
And that was presented here. And also, we're learning

416
00:25:02.026 --> 00:25:05.846
that other cells that one might not think of necessarily

417
00:25:05.936 --> 00:25:09.256
as cells that would produce neurotransmitters can do this.

418
00:25:09.306 --> 00:25:13.296
And we saw work showing that, for example, T cells and B cells can

419
00:25:13.336 --> 00:25:16.196
produce neurotransmitters like acetylcholine.

420
00:25:16.256 --> 00:25:17.946
Who would have thought that? And the

421
00:25:20.356 --> 00:25:24.176
fact that they can produce the acetylcholine is very important for regulating the

422
00:25:24.216 --> 00:25:27.976
tumor immune microenvironment. So where are we heading from

423
00:25:28.036 --> 00:25:31.736
this? Well, there's a vast complexity of neurotransmitters and their

424
00:25:31.796 --> 00:25:35.736
receptors. And so there's a ton of work to be done to really

425
00:25:35.796 --> 00:25:39.196
tease out this complexity and understand the role of

426
00:25:39.256 --> 00:25:42.596
the nervous system in cancer.

427
00:25:42.656 --> 00:25:46.606
So there are many factors that influence

428
00:25:46.606 --> 00:25:49.146
cancer phenotypes, and I'd like to close on this.

429
00:25:49.196 --> 00:25:49.596
So

430
00:25:50.696 --> 00:25:54.216
there were many presentations about genetic determinants, environmental

431
00:25:54.256 --> 00:25:57.346
exposures, aging, the microbiome, and stress.

432
00:25:57.796 --> 00:26:01.626
I'm just going to touch on some of the information that we learned from

433
00:26:01.716 --> 00:26:05.496
aging. We know that aging is the biggest risk factor

434
00:26:05.516 --> 00:26:07.796
associated with cancer, and

435
00:26:08.635 --> 00:26:12.356
specific cancer phenotypes are really associated with aging.

436
00:26:12.436 --> 00:26:16.116
And so we saw a lot of presentations that really showed us that the

437
00:26:16.176 --> 00:26:16.656
stroma,

438
00:26:17.476 --> 00:26:20.876
aged stroma, can modulate the tumor microenvironment.

439
00:26:22.076 --> 00:26:24.796
Clonal hematopoiesis, it's not passive.

440
00:26:24.916 --> 00:26:27.456
It can affect tumor phenotypes directly.

441
00:26:28.936 --> 00:26:32.386
Responses and the effects of chemotherapy and

442
00:26:32.436 --> 00:26:36.096
therapeutic agents are different in aged mice compared to young mice.

443
00:26:36.616 --> 00:26:40.566
And then we're learning about the biology of tumors that

444
00:26:40.576 --> 00:26:43.976
are associated with aging. And in this presentation, there was a

445
00:26:43.996 --> 00:26:47.696
presentation about SPEN and NOTCH2 mutant diffuse large cell

446
00:26:47.756 --> 00:26:51.736
B-cell lymphomas. These are associated with increased age.

447
00:26:51.776 --> 00:26:55.476
But in the studies, they also found that the tumors are more aggressive in females.

448
00:26:55.696 --> 00:26:59.576
And so there's a whole other layer of

449
00:26:59.616 --> 00:27:03.376
study to really understand why are these more aggressive in females

450
00:27:03.836 --> 00:27:07.796
than in males. And so I think looking ahead, a very important thing is going to

451
00:27:07.896 --> 00:27:11.876
be to use models and systems that really better reflect and take into

452
00:27:11.916 --> 00:27:15.736
account age, whether this is early, young

453
00:27:15.796 --> 00:27:17.216
age, or old age.

454
00:27:18.636 --> 00:27:22.436
So with that, I'm going to close this wrap-up.

455
00:27:22.556 --> 00:27:24.136
I would like to thank

456
00:27:25.136 --> 00:27:28.996
Corria Batijn, Michaela Eggeblad, and Sheila Stewart, who gave

