00:28:14.516 --> 00:28:18.436
And deep apologies to those whose work I wasn't able

471
00:28:18.996 --> 00:28:21.756
to cover, even if you sent me slides. I'm so sorry.

472
00:28:21.816 --> 00:28:25.636
There's so much amazing information that was presented

473
00:28:25.716 --> 00:28:29.556
here. I'd just like to take one final minute

474
00:28:29.956 --> 00:28:32.196
with a very personal reflection.

475
00:28:33.136 --> 00:28:35.956
Three years ago, I was diagnosed with estrogen

476
00:28:35.996 --> 00:28:39.436
receptor-positive, early-stage breast cancer.

477
00:28:40.096 --> 00:28:43.896
And it is really thanks to the precision,

478
00:28:44.276 --> 00:28:47.736
the partnership, the purpose, and the passion of the cancer

479
00:28:47.776 --> 00:28:51.656
research community that, as I can say, I can live my best

480
00:28:51.716 --> 00:28:55.656
life today. I've benefited from all of the science that

481
00:28:55.676 --> 00:28:59.476
has led to the identification of breast cancer subtypes.

482
00:28:59.596 --> 00:29:02.936
I actually met an AACR member, a

483
00:29:03.196 --> 00:29:06.696
50-plus-year AACR member, who developed the IHC

484
00:29:06.856 --> 00:29:10.356
assays for estrogen receptor the other day here.

485
00:29:10.676 --> 00:29:12.336
How cool is that?

486
00:29:13.456 --> 00:29:15.536
Benefited from the

487
00:29:16.956 --> 00:29:20.726
gene expression profiling, all the studies that led to that, that could

488
00:29:20.796 --> 00:29:24.176
