00:30:14.626 --> 00:30:18.546
science in that. And I think a huge credit goes to the

501
00:30:18.586 --> 00:30:22.026
program committee, who's worked tirelessly this year and

502
00:30:22.126 --> 00:30:26.086
championed certain areas and put in time to develop sessions.

503
00:30:26.486 --> 00:30:29.216
We're very grateful to them for what they've actually done.

504
00:30:30.826 --> 00:30:34.806
So, as your last slide indicated, cancer doesn't happen in

505
00:30:34.886 --> 00:30:38.286
cells, just. It happens in people.

506
00:30:38.306 --> 00:30:41.786
And people live in environments. They do things. They eat. They walk around.

507
00:30:42.466 --> 00:30:45.926
And this is an area that we are watching remarkable

508
00:30:46.046 --> 00:30:49.626
progress, and that leads to our next speaker,

509
00:30:50.946 --> 00:30:54.816
Dr. Christopher Li. So he's going to be speaking about

510
00:30:54.826 --> 00:30:58.796
prevention, early detection, population sciences, and disparities research, and

511
00:30:58.826 --> 00:31:00.316
what we've learned at the meeting. Dr.

512
00:31:00.546 --> 00:31:04.206
Li is the Vice President for Faculty Development at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer

513
00:31:04.306 --> 00:31:07.566
Center, the Associate Director for Faculty Development for the Fred

514
00:31:07.606 --> 00:31:11.426
Hutchinson-University of Washington Seattle Children's Cancer Consortium, and

515
00:31:11.486 --> 00:31:15.356
he holds the Helen G. Edison Endowed Chair for Breast Cancer

516
00:31:15.406 --> 00:31:18.186
Research at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Center. Dr.

517
00:31:18.226 --> 00:31:21.626
Li also served on the AACR Annual Meeting Program Committee.

518
00:31:21.906 --> 00:31:22.726
Let's welcome Dr. Li.

519
00:31:28.786 --> 00:31:32.266
Good afternoon, everyone. I want to start by thanking Lillian,

520
00:31:32.546 --> 00:31:35.966
Paul, and Alice for this really tremendous opportunity to share with you all the

521
00:31:35.986 --> 00:31:39.816
highlights related to cancer prevention, early detection, population

522
00:31:39.906 --> 00:31:43.786
sciences, and disparities research from this conference. Also want to thank Dr.

523
00:31:43.866 --> 00:31:47.526
Marge Foti for encouraging me to do this, as well as Dr.

524
00:31:47.726 --> 00:31:51.176
Scarlett Lin Gomez, who gave this presentation last year and shared her

525
00:31:51.366 --> 00:31:54.256
wisdom with me. I don't have any

526
00:31:54.446 --> 00:31:58.266
disclosures. And so as an epidemiologist, I love to count

527
00:31:58.346 --> 00:32:02.126
things, and so I thought it would be helpful to start by just giving you a quick

528
00:32:02.186 --> 00:32:06.176
snapshot of all of the science that was presented here under the broad umbrella of

529
00:32:06.186 --> 00:32:09.866
population sciences, which spanned yesterday's outstanding

530
00:32:09.906 --> 00:32:13.766
plenary session on early-onset cancers to over 50 talks

531
00:32:13.846 --> 00:32:17.406
in major symposia or advances in sessions, along with more than

532
00:32:17.606 --> 00:32:21.486
600 abstracts. So you may wonder how I was able to attempt

533
00:32:21.495 --> 00:32:25.256
to cover all of this incredible depth and breadth of programming, and I am

534
00:32:25.446 --> 00:32:28.786
very happy to disclose that I did not use AI at all in the development of this

535
00:32:28.806 --> 00:32:32.786
presentation. But I was very lucky to have stellar support

536
00:32:33.006 --> 00:32:36.886
from two trainees. Both of them received awards here at the annual

537
00:32:36.986 --> 00:32:39.326
meeting and presented their science as well.

538
00:32:39.926 --> 00:32:43.406
Kaylee, who is a postdoc working with me at Fred Hutch, and Vicky, who is a

539
00:32:43.466 --> 00:32:46.486
graduate student at the Huntsman Cancer Institute.

540
00:32:47.466 --> 00:32:49.086
And what I will present to you

541
00:32:50.146 --> 00:32:53.146
now really would not have been possible without their incredible support.

542
00:32:53.186 --> 00:32:55.806
So thank you both for your contributions.

543
00:32:56.346 --> 00:33:00.126
I also took the strategy of asking many of my colleagues if they would send me a

544
00:33:00.166 --> 00:33:04.106
summary of their talk to include in this presentation, and so I want to

545
00:33:04.146 --> 00:33:07.946
thank the many people who sent me those materials.

546
00:33:07.986 --> 00:33:10.966
So many, in fact, that I couldn't ultimately use them all just due to time

547
00:33:10.986 --> 00:33:14.896
restrictions and just want to recognize that this talk is really just scratching

548
00:33:14.926 --> 00:33:18.626
the surface of all of the outstanding science in these fields that were

549
00:33:18.646 --> 00:33:19.866
presented at this conference.

550
00:33:21.206 --> 00:33:25.196
So just to give you an overview of this presentation, I'm going to describe some of

551
00:33:25.226 --> 00:33:28.966
the exciting results that were shared across the very broad spectrum of population

552
00:33:29.026 --> 00:33:32.736
science, which begins with thinking about primary prevention and etiology,

553
00:33:33.286 --> 00:33:37.115
next to screening, early detection, and interception, and then treatment and

554
00:33:37.126 --> 00:33:40.666
survivorship. At this year's meeting, we also identified some

555
00:33:40.686 --> 00:33:42.356
predominant crosscutting themes

556
00:33:43.226 --> 00:33:46.966
that I'll also integrate, and these related to AI, health

557
00:33:47.046 --> 00:33:50.686
equity, and disparities, as well as community engagement.

558
00:33:51.126 --> 00:33:53.166
So I'm going to start with primary prevention.

559
00:33:53.846 --> 00:33:57.446
And with respect to this field, we do know a lot of different things that people

560
00:33:57.526 --> 00:34:01.386
can do to prevent cancer, yet there's so much work that we still need to do.

561
00:34:02.086 --> 00:34:05.386
And so I thought that a question that kind of unified a lot of the talks in this

562
00:34:05.486 --> 00:34:08.766
space were, how can we leverage things like commonly used

563
00:34:08.806 --> 00:34:11.866
medications, diet, interventions in high-risk

564
00:34:11.886 --> 00:34:15.707
populations, and even policy to prevent cancer?

565
00:34:16.246 --> 00:34:19.806
So I think a great place to start is the plenary session that was chaired by Dr.

566
00:34:20.046 --> 00:34:23.346
Chan yesterday, focused on early-onset cancers.

567
00:34:23.667 --> 00:34:27.326
In his wonderful talk, Dr. Chan reviewed the recent progress in our

568
00:34:27.335 --> 00:34:31.006
understanding of the etiology of early-onset colorectal cancer that

569
00:34:31.066 --> 00:34:34.377
included evidence linking early life obesity, insulin

570
00:34:34.446 --> 00:34:38.187
resistance, and even prenatal exposures that increase colorectal

571
00:34:38.246 --> 00:34:42.226
cancer risk, suggesting that risk is really accumulating across a lifetime

572
00:34:43.046 --> 00:34:45.726
and may begin with exposures that happen before birth.

573
00:34:46.406 --> 00:34:49.786
One specific finding from his talk that I'm highlighting here is his

574
00:34:49.806 --> 00:34:53.426
characterization of ultra-processed foods as a novel risk factor for

575
00:34:53.446 --> 00:34:57.286
early-onset colorectal cancer. He used data from the Nurses Health Study

576
00:34:57.366 --> 00:34:57.606
II

577
00:34:58.626 --> 00:35:01.986
cohort, where he identified that those in the top two

578
00:35:02.046 --> 00:35:05.186
quartiles of ultra-processed food consumption had about

579
00:35:05.326 --> 00:35:09.246
50% higher risk of early-onset colorectal adenomas.

580
00:35:09.846 --> 00:35:13.416
Unfortunately, we know that children are starting to consume these

581
00:35:13.466 --> 00:35:15.606
unhealthy foods at very young ages.

582
00:35:15.626 --> 00:35:18.856
So it's important to clarify what are the specific components of these foods that

583
00:35:18.866 --> 00:35:21.706
contribute to risk, as well as the underlying biological

584
00:35:21.786 --> 00:35:25.666
mechanisms. Another fascinating talk from this plenary was

585
00:35:25.746 --> 00:35:29.726
from Dr. Chadeayne, who presented combined evidence from both mouse and human

586
00:35:29.846 --> 00:35:33.706
studies relevant to postpartum breast cancer, which is a type of breast

587
00:35:33.726 --> 00:35:37.706
cancer associated with a particularly poor survival and carries high

588
00:35:37.786 --> 00:35:41.766
rates of liver metastasis. She presented her team's novel

589
00:35:41.846 --> 00:35:45.466
findings, showing that given that the liver plays an important role in supporting

590
00:35:45.486 --> 00:35:49.366
lactation, weaning triggers liver involution and actually

591
00:35:49.446 --> 00:35:51.786
can promote a liver pre-metastatic niche.

592
00:35:52.346 --> 00:35:55.886
So a summary of her talk was really that postpartum breast cancer warrants

593
00:35:55.926 --> 00:35:59.826
increased surveillance, treatment escalation, and targeted prevention and

594
00:35:59.886 --> 00:36:03.026
treatment strategies that really take into account this underlying

595
00:36:03.406 --> 00:36:06.986
involution biology.Another

596
00:36:07.046 --> 00:36:10.726
engaging session was this one that focused on how can we

597
00:36:10.766 --> 00:36:14.456
translate epidemiology to the clinic, and this one focused on

598
00:36:14.526 --> 00:36:18.446
aspirin. So it is very well established that aspirin reduces risk of

599
00:36:18.486 --> 00:36:22.396
colorectal cancer and other GI cancers by 30% through a number of

600
00:36:22.426 --> 00:36:25.676
different mechanisms, but there are a number of unanswered questions in this field.

601
00:36:26.426 --> 00:36:30.266
Dr. Langley described her work identifying that reducing

602
00:36:30.286 --> 00:36:33.866
platelet activation is one of aspirin's key anticancer

603
00:36:33.886 --> 00:36:37.766
effects, and so this has led her to try to pursue this question of

604
00:36:37.826 --> 00:36:41.436
can we use this information to identify which patients will

605
00:36:41.446 --> 00:36:45.326
benefit the most from aspirin? She's currently evaluating a

606
00:36:45.346 --> 00:36:48.746
biomarker, UTXM, which is a biomarker of platelet

607
00:36:48.826 --> 00:36:52.576
activation, to see if this can inform who will versus who will not

608
00:36:52.586 --> 00:36:56.346
respond to aspirin, and she's evaluating this in the ADD ASPIRIN trial

609
00:36:56.826 --> 00:36:59.946
of cancer patients. Next, Dr. Yilmaz

610
00:37:00.266 --> 00:37:03.846
described something that I had never heard about before, which is a

611
00:37:03.866 --> 00:37:07.746
recently observed paradox that while aspirin has been shown to

612
00:37:07.786 --> 00:37:11.286
improve survival when given to Stage 1 to 3 colorectal cancer

613
00:37:11.306 --> 00:37:14.586
patients, it actually has the opposite effect and reduces

614
00:37:14.606 --> 00:37:16.936
survival when given to Stage 4 patients.

615
00:37:17.246 --> 00:37:18.086
And he presented

616
00:37:18.926 --> 00:37:22.626
very exciting unpublished work exploring what are the underlying biological

617
00:37:22.706 --> 00:37:26.436
mechanisms of this paradox. And then lastly, in this session, Dr.

618
00:37:26.666 --> 00:37:29.996
Dubois presented his large body of work

619
00:37:30.306 --> 00:37:34.186
showcasing the prostaglandin E2 effects on immune

620
00:37:34.266 --> 00:37:38.026
cell biology. And as you can see in the graph here, delivery of

621
00:37:38.046 --> 00:37:41.906
celecoxib resulted in a number of changes to immune cells in the

622
00:37:41.946 --> 00:37:42.746
microenvironment.

623
00:37:44.706 --> 00:37:48.646
In another talk, Dr. Stone described the potential of a different type of

624
00:37:48.686 --> 00:37:52.646
intervention, in this case, a surgical intervention, as a strategy to prevent

625
00:37:52.666 --> 00:37:56.526
ovarian cancer. This approach is based on recent evidence

626
00:37:56.536 --> 00:37:59.886
that most ovarian cancers actually originate in the fallopian tube,

627
00:38:00.326 --> 00:38:04.266
not in the ovary itself. So salpingectomy could be

628
00:38:04.366 --> 00:38:08.326
used to prevent ovarian cancer. And actually, there was a study published just last

629
00:38:08.386 --> 00:38:12.326
month that it can reduce risk of serous ovarian cancer

630
00:38:12.346 --> 00:38:16.286
by 80%. However, uptake of salpingectomy in the US remains

631
00:38:16.306 --> 00:38:18.746
low, and there are persistent disparities.

632
00:38:19.146 --> 00:38:23.046
So to address this, Dr. Stone's team has focused on identifying

633
00:38:23.086 --> 00:38:26.906
what are the barriers to receiving this type of intervention, and she

634
00:38:26.926 --> 00:38:30.906
identified that insurance coverage and inadequate patient education were

635
00:38:30.926 --> 00:38:33.706
the primary barriers. In response to this,

636
00:38:34.586 --> 00:38:37.676
her team has developed the Outsmart Ovarian Cancer Collaborative.

637
00:38:38.046 --> 00:38:41.176
They've developed a comprehensive curriculum that addresses the structural and

638
00:38:41.206 --> 00:38:44.866
educational barriers, and she's in the process of developing a multi-site

639
00:38:44.886 --> 00:38:48.436
trial that will look at the acceptability, feasibility, and safety

640
00:38:48.826 --> 00:38:52.156
of opportunistic salpingectomy, which could have tremendous impact on

641
00:38:52.186 --> 00:38:53.966
reducing ovarian cancer.

642
00:38:55.766 --> 00:38:56.446
And then the last

643
00:38:57.806 --> 00:39:01.106
thing that I'll talk about related to cancer prevention was this very interactive

644
00:39:01.186 --> 00:39:04.886
forum that was focused on exploring policy solutions.

645
00:39:05.646 --> 00:39:09.306
So the panel here included multiple experts who

646
00:39:09.386 --> 00:39:13.306
focused on how policy solutions can have a meaningful impact on cancer

647
00:39:13.366 --> 00:39:17.286
prevention. The panel really focused primarily on lung cancer and

648
00:39:17.346 --> 00:39:21.066
highlighted how strong regulatory frameworks have meaningfully

649
00:39:21.146 --> 00:39:25.126
curbed tobacco use and that there are these emerging challenges,

650
00:39:25.466 --> 00:39:29.126
such as the introduction of e-cigarettes, but that policy, again, here, can have an

651
00:39:29.166 --> 00:39:32.566
important role. The graph that's shown here indicates

652
00:39:32.686 --> 00:39:36.486
use of e-cigarettes

653
00:39:36.566 --> 00:39:40.406
among youth and children, and when policy was implemented, shown on the

654
00:39:40.426 --> 00:39:44.206
red line, very quickly after that, you see a sharp drop in the

655
00:39:44.286 --> 00:39:48.186
use of e-cigarettes among children, just demonstrating the power

656
00:39:48.326 --> 00:39:48.946
of policy.

657
00:39:49.826 --> 00:39:53.706
They also spent quite a bit of time talking about the role of lung

658
00:39:53.746 --> 00:39:57.506
cancer screening. It's a very effective strategy, but we could do even

659
00:39:57.606 --> 00:40:01.326
better. They talked about how we could avert an additional 88,000 lung

660
00:40:01.406 --> 00:40:05.106
cancers in the United States in the next five years if we were able to broaden the

661
00:40:05.166 --> 00:40:08.986
criteria and accessibility of lung cancer screening.

662
00:40:09.326 --> 00:40:12.766
So this session really just highlighted how policy solutions are a

663
00:40:12.826 --> 00:40:16.526
necessary step for realizing many of the benefits

664
00:40:16.606 --> 00:40:19.326
of our prevention and screening efforts.

665
00:40:20.296 --> 00:40:23.246
So I'll now turn to cancer screening.

666
00:40:23.546 --> 00:40:27.306
I think we all recognize that when done well, cancer screening saves

667
00:40:27.366 --> 00:40:30.876
lives, but there are certain issues with cancer screening that we're grappling

668
00:40:30.926 --> 00:40:34.826
with. One is that we're still largely using a one-size-fits-all approach for

669
00:40:34.866 --> 00:40:38.606
cancer screening. Overdiagnosis and overtreatment can be persistent

670
00:40:38.726 --> 00:40:42.206
issues. We also can miss aggressive cancers by screening,

671
00:40:43.046 --> 00:40:46.026
and there are many types of cancers where we still don't have a useful screening

672
00:40:46.066 --> 00:40:49.946
test. So I think an overarching question here that many of the talks

673
00:40:49.986 --> 00:40:53.286
tried to address is, can we make cancer screening both more

674
00:40:53.346 --> 00:40:57.306
efficacious and more efficient through implementing risk-based

675
00:40:57.346 --> 00:41:00.946
precision screening? And also, are there new screening tools that could be

676
00:41:01.006 --> 00:41:01.546
impactful?

677
00:41:02.806 --> 00:41:06.696
So I think in order to realize the promise of precision screening, we need

678
00:41:06.806 --> 00:41:10.766
accurate models that can be used to inform who should be screened and

679
00:41:10.806 --> 00:41:13.206
how frequently they should be screened. And Dr.

680
00:41:13.306 --> 00:41:17.226
Song presented his work on the potential benefits of risk-based screening

681
00:41:17.246 --> 00:41:20.966
for colorectal cancer. He's developed a risk score to guide

682
00:41:21.006 --> 00:41:24.166
subsequent screening among those who've just had a negative screening

683
00:41:24.176 --> 00:41:26.826
colonoscopy.

684
00:41:27.646 --> 00:41:31.496
As shown in this figure, the risk that high-risk patients,

685
00:41:31.506 --> 00:41:35.346
based on this score, have 10 years after their negative colonoscopy

686
00:41:35.766 --> 00:41:39.306
is only reached after 25 years among the low-risk

687
00:41:39.386 --> 00:41:43.266
patients, suggesting that the low-risk patients likely don't

688
00:41:43.326 --> 00:41:46.846
need to receive a repeat screening colonoscopy for

689
00:41:47.626 --> 00:41:50.226
maybe even more than a decade after those who are high risk.

690
00:41:50.766 --> 00:41:54.426
However, he recognized that the existing models require further improvement,

691
00:41:54.746 --> 00:41:58.646
and he is integrating use of AI as well as electronic health

692
00:41:58.706 --> 00:42:02.286
record data to try and improve model performance and achieve

693
00:42:02.546 --> 00:42:06.086
clinical utility.A fascinating talk

694
00:42:06.446 --> 00:42:09.926
was this one given by Dr. Plon, who shared her work on the

695
00:42:09.966 --> 00:42:13.786
development of newborn screening that incorporates testing for genetic

696
00:42:13.866 --> 00:42:16.346
variants that are relevant to pediatric cancer.

697
00:42:16.866 --> 00:42:20.766
She described that we, in the US, do universal screening for over 50

698
00:42:20.806 --> 00:42:24.666
conditions in newborns, but none of these screens include

699
00:42:24.686 --> 00:42:28.466
screening for cancer. And this is despite evidence to

700
00:42:28.506 --> 00:42:32.396
suggest that newborn screening could reduce cancer death before age 20

701
00:42:32.426 --> 00:42:33.266
by 8%.

702
00:42:34.246 --> 00:42:37.726
And she described a retrospective study from Michigan, which found that

703
00:42:37.966 --> 00:42:40.946
7% of pediatric cancers could be detected by screening,

704
00:42:41.886 --> 00:42:45.726
including 80% of bilateral retinoblastomas, and that's what's shown in the

705
00:42:45.766 --> 00:42:49.676
graph here. So her and her team are in the process of establishing

706
00:42:49.726 --> 00:42:53.626
additional prospective data to support what she envisions as

707
00:42:53.706 --> 00:42:57.646
a large-scale clinical trial that will use an ultra-low-cost

708
00:42:57.746 --> 00:43:01.606
pooled targeting sequencing pipeline that, if ultimately

709
00:43:01.646 --> 00:43:05.375
implemented, has the potential to prevent pediatric cancer deaths.

710
00:43:06.186 --> 00:43:10.096
And then, the last vignette I will describe related to cancer screening is

711
00:43:10.126 --> 00:43:12.646
this also quite interesting talk by Dr.

712
00:43:12.686 --> 00:43:14.586
Ayala, who is a computer scientist.

713
00:43:15.246 --> 00:43:18.846
He described how his work is focused on three goals.

714
00:43:19.306 --> 00:43:22.986
One, using available data to better inform patient disease status.

715
00:43:23.506 --> 00:43:27.366
Two, developing new guidelines, risk models, and algorithms

716
00:43:27.406 --> 00:43:30.956
with these data. And three, really proving that the AI models

717
00:43:31.066 --> 00:43:34.626
work. So his team has developed what they're calling Pillar Zero,

718
00:43:35.066 --> 00:43:39.006
which is a free next generation foundation model applied

719
00:43:39.066 --> 00:43:41.956
to radiology that he has shown outperforms

720
00:43:43.126 --> 00:43:46.966
all of its competitors. And basically what this approach does is that it can be

721
00:43:47.026 --> 00:43:49.426
applied to any type of imaging data.

722
00:43:49.486 --> 00:43:53.406
He gave examples of abdominal and pelvic CTs as well as

723
00:43:53.606 --> 00:43:57.346
chest CTs. And basically, you can use this model to say, "In this

724
00:43:57.366 --> 00:44:01.306
CT scan, is there evidence of a pancreatic tumor?

725
00:44:01.406 --> 00:44:05.186
Is there evidence of a prostate cancer?" And so he's continuing to work to

726
00:44:05.226 --> 00:44:09.186
refine these models, again, towards ultimate clinical

727
00:44:09.446 --> 00:44:09.886
utility.

728
00:44:11.426 --> 00:44:14.816
So, I'll now turn to the area of early detection.

729
00:44:15.386 --> 00:44:18.446
There's certainly a lot of evidence to support the promise of early

730
00:44:18.486 --> 00:44:22.456
detection, but this field is hampered by many challenges that are outlined

731
00:44:22.526 --> 00:44:26.316
here. And so I think a common question that presentations in this

732
00:44:26.406 --> 00:44:30.206
space ought to address is how do we overcome these challenges in the field of

733
00:44:30.226 --> 00:44:33.805
early detection to realize its potential to reduce the burden of

734
00:44:33.876 --> 00:44:37.866
cancer? Obviously, a very hot topic, our multi-cancer early detection

735
00:44:37.946 --> 00:44:38.246
tests.

736
00:44:39.226 --> 00:44:42.686
Probably many of you in the room read this article in "The New York Times" from a

737
00:44:42.746 --> 00:44:46.546
few months ago, which reported the failure of the

738
00:44:46.606 --> 00:44:50.356
GRAIL multi-cancer early detection test to reach its clinical utility

739
00:44:50.466 --> 00:44:54.326
endpoints. And so this forum that was held last night was a very

740
00:44:54.406 --> 00:44:58.306
interactive session that focused on what is the state of where we are

741
00:44:58.386 --> 00:45:01.186
now, how do we take stock of the results that have

742
00:45:02.166 --> 00:45:05.926
come out, and how can we potentially realize the hope of this

743
00:45:06.026 --> 00:45:09.996
strategy? So there was a great panel of three experts in this

744
00:45:10.026 --> 00:45:13.946
field who really range from those who maintain

745
00:45:14.026 --> 00:45:17.966
very high enthusiasm for the promise of MCEDs to those who remain actually quite

746
00:45:18.006 --> 00:45:20.546
skeptical about their ultimate potential utility.

747
00:45:21.426 --> 00:45:24.986
There was, I think, some agreement that these tests do have

748
00:45:25.066 --> 00:45:28.626
promise and that promise is real, but that we need to make sure that when we're

749
00:45:28.686 --> 00:45:32.436
evaluating them, we're using rigorous study designs, and that we're also

750
00:45:32.566 --> 00:45:36.046
very clearly and transparently communicating their benefits and

751
00:45:36.106 --> 00:45:40.076
harms to the public. There was a recognition that the harms of these tests

752
00:45:40.106 --> 00:45:44.026
are also real, at both the individual and population levels, but also that

753
00:45:44.046 --> 00:45:47.976
there is an urgency here. We want to try to be able to detect cancer early

754
00:45:48.006 --> 00:45:51.746
to save lives, and we don't want to have to wait another 10 to 15 years for the

755
00:45:51.756 --> 00:45:55.306
next set of trials to be complete. And so how do we balance that sense of

756
00:45:55.366 --> 00:45:59.036
urgency with the need for rigor? And so I think there

757
00:45:59.266 --> 00:46:02.726
is a lot of promise, I think, still in the space, but, obviously

758
00:46:02.786 --> 00:46:06.736
caution in how we move forward. While obviously a lot of

759
00:46:06.746 --> 00:46:10.036
interest in multi-cancer tests, there are also many people

760
00:46:10.106 --> 00:46:13.566
still working on single site early detection strategies.

761
00:46:14.586 --> 00:46:16.466
And I'm highlighting this talk from Dr.

762
00:46:16.666 --> 00:46:20.406
Simeone, who recognized that we've made very little progress in

763
00:46:20.446 --> 00:46:24.326
improving the dismal survival rates that pancreatic cancer patients currently

764
00:46:24.386 --> 00:46:24.685
face.

765
00:46:25.685 --> 00:46:29.246
Early detection of pancreas cancer remains an important priority,

766
00:46:29.766 --> 00:46:33.606
and it holds promise in that we know that the five-year survival rate for

767
00:46:33.706 --> 00:46:36.366
Stage 1A pancreas cancers is actually 84%.

768
00:46:36.986 --> 00:46:38.896
So in order to address this gap, Dr.

769
00:46:39.126 --> 00:46:42.866
Simeone talked about the PRECEDE study, which is the world's largest

770
00:46:42.926 --> 00:46:46.546
longitudinal study of individuals at high risk for pancreas

771
00:46:46.606 --> 00:46:50.406
cancer. There are over 65 participating

772
00:46:50.446 --> 00:46:53.786
institutions. They're trying to recruit 20,000 patients.

773
00:46:54.646 --> 00:46:58.246
And they're doing germline testing as well as performing image-based screening.

774
00:46:59.086 --> 00:47:01.086
So far, she presented very promising results.

775
00:47:01.116 --> 00:47:04.476
Seventy-two percent of the screen-detected lesions were Stage 1,

776
00:47:05.106 --> 00:47:07.716
which is much better than we see in the general population.

777
00:47:08.046 --> 00:47:11.586
And really that this PRECEDE study could be an invaluable resource

778
00:47:12.186 --> 00:47:16.026
for testing and validating promising early detection strategies that are

779
00:47:16.066 --> 00:47:18.516
now emerging for pancreas cancer.

780
00:47:19.826 --> 00:47:22.116
So now I'll turn to cancer interception.

781
00:47:22.286 --> 00:47:24.826
This was actually a very hot topic at this meeting.

782
00:47:24.886 --> 00:47:28.416
So for those who are not fully familiar with what cancer interception means,

783
00:47:28.806 --> 00:47:32.736
it's really the idea that we can identify and

784
00:47:32.786 --> 00:47:36.755
then treat early pre-cancerous lesions to prevent them from

785
00:47:36.786 --> 00:47:39.966
ultimately becoming cancer. So the poster child for interception is

786
00:47:40.046 --> 00:47:43.826
colonoscopy and the removal of adenomas and polyps.

787
00:47:43.866 --> 00:47:47.066
By taking out those pre-cancerous lesions, we are

788
00:47:47.106 --> 00:47:50.846
intercepting the development of future cancers.

789
00:47:51.326 --> 00:47:55.255
So a question here across cancer interception talks was

790
00:47:55.366 --> 00:47:59.346
what are emerging opportunities to reduce the burden of cancer through cancer

791
00:47:59.386 --> 00:48:03.244
interception?There was a great talk given by my colleague, Dr.

792
00:48:03.914 --> 00:48:07.394
Nora Disis, on the promise of vaccines in this space.

793
00:48:07.754 --> 00:48:11.454
And she talked about the fact that vaccines can induce memory that lasts

794
00:48:11.474 --> 00:48:15.334
decades, T cells can be specific to particular targets with limited

795
00:48:15.414 --> 00:48:18.593
toxicity, and that they can also travel to any type of disease.

796
00:48:19.004 --> 00:48:22.634
And she gave an overview of many of the different current vaccine

797
00:48:22.674 --> 00:48:26.234
trials, Phase I and II studies in Lynch syndrome patients,

798
00:48:26.854 --> 00:48:28.554
as well as for DCIS,

799
00:48:29.474 --> 00:48:33.094
which in early results show immunogenicity and early efficacy

800
00:48:33.794 --> 00:48:37.634
with minimal adverse events. So this figure that she had in her

801
00:48:37.674 --> 00:48:41.214
talk really, I think, shows what her vision is for a

802
00:48:41.254 --> 00:48:45.154
near-term future where we're able to use cancer-related vaccines

803
00:48:45.634 --> 00:48:45.994
for

804
00:48:46.874 --> 00:48:49.194
primary prevention as prophylactics,

805
00:48:50.534 --> 00:48:54.194
for interception, as well as to prevent future recurrences.

806
00:48:54.254 --> 00:48:55.474
So I think really a very exciting

807
00:48:56.354 --> 00:48:58.274
time in the area of cancer vaccines.

808
00:48:59.814 --> 00:49:03.694
I think also critical to the field of interception is identifying

809
00:49:03.814 --> 00:49:05.824
promising targets for interception. And Dr.

810
00:49:06.574 --> 00:49:08.614
Lee presented just

811
00:49:09.654 --> 00:49:13.314
very elegant work that employs innovative genetically engineered mouse

812
00:49:13.374 --> 00:49:16.854
models, patient-derived samples, and multi-omic profiling to

813
00:49:16.914 --> 00:49:20.694
identify mechanistic drivers for early-onset basal-like

814
00:49:20.774 --> 00:49:24.534
triple-negative breast cancer, to identify opportunities for

815
00:49:24.574 --> 00:49:27.274
early interception that was quite exciting to see.

816
00:49:28.454 --> 00:49:32.414
And then lastly, with respect to interception, is this example from Dr.

817
00:49:32.634 --> 00:49:35.094
Drapkin, whose work is in ovarian cancer.

818
00:49:35.514 --> 00:49:39.294
Again, recognizing that high-grade serous ovarian cancer

819
00:49:39.354 --> 00:49:43.254
arises in the fallopian tube, there are these early lesions, so-called

820
00:49:43.294 --> 00:49:46.334
STIC lesions, that have variable clinical risk.

821
00:49:46.754 --> 00:49:50.714
So the translational goal of Dr. Drapkin's work is to try to define

822
00:49:50.754 --> 00:49:54.734
early genomic and microenvironmental features of these lesions that

823
00:49:54.774 --> 00:49:58.114
could then enable both early detection and interception.

824
00:49:58.194 --> 00:50:00.934
And so he's using multimodal spatial

825
00:50:01.574 --> 00:50:04.534
strategies on these tubal precursors and

826
00:50:04.594 --> 00:50:08.294
he presented quite robust data showing that

827
00:50:08.314 --> 00:50:11.854
early lesions show parallel genomic and immune

828
00:50:11.894 --> 00:50:15.754
trajectories, providing, I think, a promising framework

829
00:50:15.794 --> 00:50:18.654
for risk stratification and interception.

830
00:50:20.634 --> 00:50:23.894
The next topic I'm going to cover is cancer disparities.

831
00:50:23.914 --> 00:50:27.634
Really could have picked any cancer to highlight persistent disparities that exist

832
00:50:27.674 --> 00:50:30.864
